commentTextItems.html: pierces the infield and India have sealed the most unlikely win! Full and into the pads, leans in again and gets it to square leg's left this time, past his outstretched left arm

commentPostTextItems.html: Mark Taylor says he was happy with the runs and that Australia just didn't bowl well enough with the wet ball at the end, while crediting Srinath for his batting. Sachin Tendulkar says he was happy with the overall performance but the batsmen could do better. He says Srinath and Kumble batted like champions before heading over and accepting his Man of the Match award. That concludes our coverage of this classic. Thanks for joining us and we'll see you soon!

Dinesh Singh: "If I am not mistaken, this match happened near Diwali days. I was just 7 years old and an ardent cricket fan. Remember watching this match with my entire family. Getting goosebumps and watery eyes remembering some of the faint memories of this match. So nostalgic! Thank you so much Cricinfo!"
Navin: "Can still remember Srinath's six with people leaving the stadium"

6:25pm What an effort from India's premier bowlers - a dream finish with the bat in front of their very own. Australia did splendidly at the start of the innings to reduce India to 48 for 4. Then, some decisions went against them - arguably one of the biggest factors tonight - but they came back again, getting 3 for 7, including the wicket of Tendulkar, who was once again the lone resistance. But with 52 needed off 47, India have won with seven balls to spare.

commentPostTextItems.html: That is fifty for the stand. In 38 balls. What a partnership this has been. Australia cannot concede any more runs if they want to win this.

misses out on a juicy full toss. Nerves from the inexperienced bowler? Slower ball goes wrong and floats up at axing height for Srinath, who mistimes and can only get a single at deep square
short of a length into the body, watchfully nudged into the leg side

clears midwicket! That's a good shot from Srinath, who might have been expecting the back of a length ball based on McGrath's change-ups last over. Because he was quickly in position for the pull and he nailed the connection
short of a length outside off, gets back in the crease and flat-bats this to the deep midwicket fielder

commentPostTextItems.html: Good over McGrath, he's put a stopper on the boundaries at the very least. But India will be happy getting six against him. Taylor with the conundrum now - does he go with the young fast bowler or does he go with Waugh's experience? There are potential downsides to both, but for now he's gone with pace against tailenders. Here is Gillespie.
